{"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"language":"GRK","version":"GNA","book":"Joh","segmentID":"I043","segment":{"content":{"document":{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"JOHN"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"marks":[{"object":"mark","type":"bold"}],"object":"leaf","text":"That you may believe"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"Jesus revealed as the Son of God, full of grace and truth"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"subtitle"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":""}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"How to read John"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"subtitle"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"In Jesus’ day, as in ours, there were many competing belief systems—all trying to connect with a spiritual reality beyond ourselves. One major religion features a god of power and revenge; another worships one that is silent and indifferent to the suffering of people; still another offers a god that is mysterious and unknowable, absorbing all of humanity into a great cosmic ocean of oneness. Some people worship “gods” of possessions, fame, and entertainment. Only one faith—Christianity—worships an amazing, personal being known primarily for his sacrificial love. This book profiles that unique God, revealed in the person of Jesus Christ—God in human flesh."}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"\tIn this account of Jesus’ life, you will be confronted with some astonishing claims about who he is and what he came to do. John tells us that he has selected only a few of the many noteworthy things Jesus did in order to help us understand who Jesus is. He records only seven miracles, climaxing in Jesus’ resurrection. For John these signs give indisputable proof that Jesus is the Son of God. There is more, John says, but “"},{"marks":[{"object":"mark","type":"blueHighlight"}],"object":"leaf","text":"the whole world could not contain the books that would be written"},{"object":"leaf","text":"” (Joh 21:25) had he recorded all of Jesus’ mighty signs. So why has he told us these select stories? To elicit a response of faith in our hearts, “"},{"marks":[{"object":"mark","type":"blueHighlight"}],"object":"leaf","text":"so that you may continue to believe that Jesus is the Messiah, the Son of God, and that by believing in him you will have life by the power of his name"},{"object":"leaf","text":"” (Joh 20:31)."}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"\tNote some unique features of John’s gospel. He uses the images of light and life to describe God’s activity in the world. He includes several of Jesus’ sermons not found in the other gospels (Jesus in Joh 3:10-21; 5:19-47; 9:41-10:5; 10:7-18,25-30; 13:7-21,26-27,31-36,38-14:4; 14:6-7,9-21,23-16; 16:19-28,31-33; 17:1-26). He highlights Jesus’ many “"},{"marks":[{"object":"mark","type":"blueHighlight"}],"object":"leaf","text":"I am"},{"object":"leaf","text":"” statements. Jesus declares he is the Messiah, the bread of life from heaven, the one sent by God, the light of the world, the door, the good shepherd, the Son of God, the resurrection, the life, the way, the truth, the true vine, and the King of the Jews. These statements should give you ample reason to believe!"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":""}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"Who wrote this book?"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"subtitle"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"John, the apostle—one of the original twelve disciples of Jesus."}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":""}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"When and where was it written?"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"subtitle"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"Sometime between "},{"marks":[{"object":"mark","type":"smallcaps"}],"object":"leaf","text":"ad"},{"object":"leaf","text":" 80 and 95 (although some scholars argue that the book can be dated as early as the 50s and no later than 70). John was probably in Ephesus, a city located in modern-day Turkey."}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":""}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"To whom was it written?"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"subtitle"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"Non-Jewish followers of Jesus, particularly those struggling with Greek philosophies, which taught that salvation comes through special knowledge and that Jesus was divine but not truly human. John insists that salvation is received by believing in God’s Son, Jesus, who came in human flesh."}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":""}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"Why was it written?"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"subtitle"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"John himself clearly states his goal (see Joh 20:31). He writes the gospel with an evangelistic objective. He wants people to have eternal life by knowing Jesus Christ."}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":""}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"SourceView Insights"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"subtitle"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"In John, three of the twelve disciples have no speaking part: Matthew-Levi, James son of Alphaeus, and Simon the Zealot (see the introduction to Matthew). Nine do in John—much more than the other three gospel accounts. The disciple with the smallest speaking part is James—his own brother! Isn’t that typical of a sibling?"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"\tNote the number of words attributed to each disciple within each gospel:"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":""}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"paragraph"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"\tMatthew"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"paragraph"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"\tMark"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"paragraph"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"Luke"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"paragraph"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"\tJohn"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"paragraph"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"}],"object":"block","type":"table_row"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"Simon Peter"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"paragraph"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"###"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"###"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"###"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"###"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"}],"object":"block","type":"table_row"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"Andrew"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"paragraph"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"-"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"paragraph"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"###"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"###"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"###"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"}],"object":"block","type":"table_row"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"John the Disciple"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"paragraph"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"###"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"###"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"###"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"###"}],"object":"text"}],"object":"block","type":"speech"}],"object":"block","type":"table_cell"}],"object":"block","type":"table_row"},{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"nodes":[{"leaves":[{"object":"leaf","text":"James the Disciple"}],"object":"text"